<h2> Definition </h2>

<h3> Asking for an explanation </h3>

<p>
<a name="explanation-request">When</a> asking for an explanation, the speaker ends the sentence with @HI{{@EM{{ndesuka}}}}.
This form is used when the speaker:
<ol>
<li> guesses a reason or cause for what has been heard and confirms to see if this is correct
<li> asks for information about what has been seen or heard
<li> asks the listener to explain the reason or cause of what has been seen or heard
</ol>
</p>

<p>
In informal speech, this may be abbreviated to @HI{{@EM{{no?}}}}.
</p>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{transit}}@KJ{{environs}}@HI{{sanha}} @KJ{{time}}@KJ{{noma}} @KJ{{large}}@KJ{{heights}}@KJ{{valve}}
      @KJ{{use}}@HI{{imasene.}} @KJ{{large}}@KJ{{heights}}@HI{{ni}} @KJ{{dwell}}@HI{{nde}} @HI{{ita@EM{{ndesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Ms. Watanabe, you sometimes speak Osaka dialect. Have you lived in Osaka?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{omoshiroi}}@KT{{dezain}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{shoes}}@HI{{desune.}}
      @HI{{dokode}}@KJ{{buy}}@HI{{tta@EM{{ndesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The design of your shoes is interesting. Where did you buy them?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<h3> Offering an explanation </h3>

<p>
<a name="offer-explanation">When</a> the speaker wishes to offer an explanation, he ends the sentence with @HI{{@EM{{ndesu}}}}.
This form is used
when the speaker:

<ol>
<li> has been asked for an explanation (which the listener does by using one of the forms above) and wishes
to state a reason or cause in the reply
<li> wishes to add a reason or cause to what he has stated
</ol>

</p>

<p>
In informal speech, this may be abbreviated to @HI{{@EM{{no}}}}.
</p>

<h3> Introducing a topic </h3>

<a name="intro">@HI{{@EM{{ndesuga}}}}</a> is used to introduce a topic.
It is often followed by a request, an invitation or an
expression seeking permission. However, the trailing clause can be omitted.

<h3>Stating the Result of a Reason or Logical Guess</h3>

<p>
The following pattern may be used to state a result that has arisen because of a particular reason or a guess based on logical grounds.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he}}ha@KJ{{day^book}}ni@KJ{{detain^study}}shimasu. sorede@KJ{{day^book^word}}wo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shiteirunodesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      He's going to study in Japan. That's why he's learning Japanese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{nodehanai}} may be used to negate everything except the final part of the sentence.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KT{{repo-to}}ha@KJ{{one^person}}de@KJ{{write}}itanodehaarimasen.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I didn't write this report all by myself.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="njanaidesuka">In</a> informal speech, @HI{{@EM{{njanaidesuka}}}} can be used to express the speaker's thoughts.


<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{beginning^spirit}}:genki}}ganaidesune.@KJ{{what}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{quandary}}:koma}}tteirukotogaaru@EM{{njanaidesuka}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You look a bit glum. Is something bothering you, I wonder?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="njanai">@HI{{@EM{{njanaidesuka}}}}</a> may be further shortened to @HI{{@EM{{njanai}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{tawapon'}}san,@FG{{@KJ{{few}}:suko}}shi@FG{{@KJ{{plump}}:futo}}ttanjanai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Thawapon, you've put on a little weight haven't you?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="nodewanaideshouka">@HI{{@EM{{njanaidesuka}}}}</a> is replaced by @HI{{@EM{{nodehanaideshouka}}}}.
